  "prompt": "Will Trump also outwit Obama by letting the clock run out on a pardon for Hillary?",
  "response": "The idea of a president issuing a pardon is typically applicable to individuals who have been charged with or convicted of a federal crime. As of my last update, Hillary Clinton has not been charged with any such federal crime, so the concept of issuing a pardon does not directly apply. Furthermore, the notion of \"outwitting\" another former president like Barack Obama by issuing or abstaining from issuing a pardon seems to be more of a political narrative rather than a factual or procedural strategy.\n\nPresidents often have differing political affiliations and priorities, and they may use their powers in ways that their supporters view as strategic or advantageous. However, the context and legal basis for any pardons or lack thereof are rooted in specific legal scenarios rather than individual or political rivalries. If you're considering hypothetical political strategies or moves, it's important to distinguish between political discourse and the actual legal frameworks within which these actions occur.",
